sentences: The band was most notable for a six-song EP entitled You Are An E.P. in 1983 (see discography).
In 1984, Decter wrote and submitted a song titled "Roddy Pipers Rowdy Hearts Club Band" for The Wrestling Album.
Although the song did not make the record, it was later included on the Four Bands That Could Change The World compilation album released in 1985 on Gasatanka Records.
F did several small east coast tours during the 1980s, touring with the Ramones, White_Flag, and Flag of Democracy.
In 1988, F had a 7-inch vinyl record released on Mystic Records, titled Mess You Up, which included a credited guest appearance by famed eccentric ukelele player Tiny Tim.
Previously in 1985, Decter had also joined Disorderly Conduct, a metal-edged punk band also from South Florida featuring a 17 year old Casey Chaos.
In 1986, Disorderly Conduct released a full-length album entitled Amen and was featured on the Flipside compilation album Flipside's Vinyl Fanzine 2.
In 1990, Disorderly Conduct relocated from Florida to Los Angeles and became Amen in Los Angeles, with Casey Chaos on vocals.

Unable to secure a record deal during the 1990s Seattle grunge era, Decter amicably split from Amen and joined the Ex-Idols where he began co-writing with talented singer/songwriter Gary Finneran aka Gary X.
The Ex-Idols released their major label debut Social Kill in 1994 on Sony Music, and toured with English punk band the U.K. Subs.
In 1996 the Ex-Idols were released from Sony Music before recording their second full-length album independently entitled WhoWeAre.
In 1999, Decter began producing a local access television show for Time Warner Cable entitled Huntington Street Television.

In 2000, Decter toured and played in various friends bands including Drown, Diatribe, and ex-bandmate and co-songwriter Gary Finneran's post Ex-Idols group Tuscaurora, and in 2004 Decter rejoined Casey Chaos in their group Amen.

In 2000, Decter toured and played in various friends bands including Drown, Diatribe, and ex-bandmate and co-songwriter Gary Finneran's post Ex-Idols group Tuscaurora, and in 2004 Decter rejoined Casey Chaos in their group Amen.
In 2006 the band was asked to perform on The Henry Rollins Show.
The performance aired internationally on July 13, 2007, on the 14th episode of Season 2, with the band performing their songs "Coma America" and "Liberation".

As a result of their appearance on The Henry Rollins Show, Amen was asked to co-headline the Damnation Festival with Kreator at Leeds in London, UK, in October 2007 - the festival began their European tour.
On May 10, 2009, Decter's close friend and Ex-Idols singer/songwriter Gary X Finneran died of suicide.
On July 15, 2009, a track from the second Ex-Idols album WhoWeAre was featured in Season 5 Episode 15 of the television series Rescue Me on FX, starring Denis Leary.
In 2012, Decter was recognized as a Master Mason by the Orange Grove Masonic Lodge #293
In 2014, Amen re-united to perform at the Slipknot Knotfest festival in California with Stone Sour's Roy Mayorga on drums.

Also in 2013, the band's original 1983 release "You Are An EP" regained popularity with several vinyl and CD re-releases of the record including a double CD discography titled Burn The World into Ashes And Sweep It Under The Kitchen Rug (see discography).

In 2020, Decter was featured in two separate episodes of Cornette's Drive-Thru, a popular weekly podcast hosted by professional wrestling career veteran Jim Cornette with song submissions that featured Decter on guitar and vocals.

Thirty years after the debut of Decter's south Florida band F, a 2014 edition of the Miami New Times voted F one of Miami's Best Hardcore Bands of All Time.

Duke Decter is an American entertainment producer, former 1980s American hardcore punk guitarist and current producer of the No Uncertain Terms podcast for the non-profit organization U.S. Term Limits.
Decter started his career at 15 years of age in the South Florida hardcore punk band F.
Previously in 1985, Decter had also joined Disorderly Conduct, a metal-edged punk band also from South Florida featuring a 17 year old Casey Chaos.
That same year, Decter was voted "best new hardcore guitarist" in the fanzine Famous Hardcore of Punkland.
The show ran bi-weekly for two years, with segments and acting contributed by co-writers/actors Greg Mollin, Matt Dickey, Chris Johnson, and Donny Smith.

The show also featured interviews with local MMA trainers and fighters working for a fast-growing fight promotion called the Ultimate Fighting Championship, now the UFC, where Decter would meet and interview David Tank Abbott, with whom he would later start a popular podcast (see below).
I was done with music ten years ago but had to come back because he (Casey) is so much the real deal.
I am sacrificing my personal life to do this.
I look forward to the day we organize to listen, laugh, and talk about the great moments and music which made my awesome, good-hearted friend who was Gary 'X' Finneran so legendary.

Following a permanent hearing loss incident, Decter put down his guitar and began a podcast titled The Proving Ground with UFC fight legend David Tank Abbott, whom he had previously met and interviewed while producing Huntington Street Television in the late 1990s in Huntington Beach, California.

On the heels of the success of The Proving Ground with Tank Abbott podcast, Decter was picked up by the non-partisan political activist group U.S. Term Limits, and began producing the No Uncertain Terms podcast, featuring updates concerning the grass-roots term limits movement in the US, whose primary focus is to limit the number of years served by all members of Congress.
